{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015ZWqpzX3BEfB4GHj4Xbhws","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1: The generated function signature matches the expected interface (parameter names, types, return type) specified in the description.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: Does this fail only when multiple modules interact? No — this is about whether the LLM output parsing/extraction logic correctly identifies and validates the function signature. This could be a unit-level concern if we're testing the parsing logic, but the actual signature matching depends on what the LLM generates.\n- REAL-INFRA: Does it depend on OS, real network? No subprocess needed.\n\n\n- MOCK-HIDE: If I mock the LLM to always return a correct signature, I'm not actually testing whether the real LLM follows the interface specification. The core question is whether the LLM genuinely produces code matching the spec, which a stub would always pass.\n- LLM-DEP: This behavior fundamentally depends on what the real LLM generates — the signature matching is only meaningful if the LLM actually produces the right output.\n\nThe behavior is about whether the generated function signature matches the expected interface, which requires real LLM output to test properly. With a mock, I'd just get whatever I programmed it to return, so I couldn't verify the LLM actually follows the spec. This is an agentic-level test because it depends on the LLM's actual output quality.\n\nFor the second behavior about passing test cases, I need multiple components working together: the LLM generation, code execution, test runner, and refinement loop. This is more complex than just signature matching.\n\nNow looking at the third behavior about refinement — the key is whether failure messages from the test runner get correctly passed into the next LLM prompt. This requires the test execution and prompt construction to work together properly.\n\nI can verify this with a stub LLM by inspecting what prompt it actually receives, so I don't need a real LLM to catch this integration point. The test runner and prompt builder need to be wired together, but mocking the LLM won't hide the failure.\n\nFor the fourth behavior about the retry limit, I need to check whether the service properly tracks failed attempts and stops after three tries. logic, the counter, and the error structure builder to work together.\n- REAL-INFRA: The key is the retry counter and structured error response. We don't need real LLM or real code execution — we can stub both to always fail.\n- MOCK-HIDE: If we stub the LLM to always return failing code, and stub the test runner to always report failure, we can verify the retry behavior and error structure.\n- LLM-DEP: No — we're testing the control flow (stop at 3), not LLM quality.\n\nThis is Integration — stub LLM + stub test runner, verify 3 attempts and structured error.\n\n**Behavior 5: The full loop — generate, test, refine, test again — produces a working implementation for a function that a single LLM call typically gets wrong.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is explicitly about the full pipeline.\n- REAL-INFRA: Running the generated code requires real code execution.\n- LLM-DEP: The refinement loop only demonstrates improvement if we're using a real LLM that can actually improve on feedback — a stub can't show that the loop makes the code better.\n- MULTI-STEP: Yes, explicitly — generate, test, refine, test again. Multiple agentic steps.\n\nThis is Workflow.\n\nNow I'm assigning probabilities to each behavior. For Behavior 1, the question is whether I'm testing LLM output quality or just parsing logic — if it's about whether the LLM produces the right signature, that's Agentic, but if I'm just testing the parsing, it could be Integration. I'm leaning toward Agentic at 0.7 probability.\n\nFor Behavior 2, this involves multiple LLM calls and code execution, so it's primarily Workflow at 0.65 probability. The phrase \"on the first or a subsequent attempt\" suggests potential iteration, which pushes it toward Workflow rather than just Agentic. The system needs to actually run tests and potentially retry, which requires real infrastructure.\n\nBehavior 3 is Integration-level because it's testing how the test runner's output flows into the next prompt. Behavior 4 is also Integration since it's testing the control flow between the test runner and the stopping condition with stubbed dependencies. Behavior 5 represents the full end-to-end loop where the system produces working code, so that's solidly Workflow.\n\nNow I need to think through plan_consistent for each behavior to determine which tests actually validate the plan.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9911,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9911},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"96de98a5-37a6-4f51-9ce0-9ef3eef720d8","uuid":"4089dd77-2c6e-4230-add3-e8055be23981"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015ZWqpzX3BEfB4GHj4Xbhws","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Mc6bFaehsmbFP4UK21FbSw","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The generated function signature matches the expected interface (parameter names, types, return type) specified in the description.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"MOCK-MISS: A single function that parses LLM output could be unit-tested, but the behavior asserts that the *generated* signature matches — it's about LLM output quality, not just parsing logic. LLM-DEP: A stub LLM can be made to always return a correct signature, so any test using a stub will always pass regardless of whether the real model respects the interface spec. The real failure mode is that the LLM ignores or misinterprets type/parameter constraints in the prompt. Only a real LLM call can expose that. REJECTION of Integration/Unit: We could test the prompt-construction or signature-extraction logic at Integration, but that does not catch the behavior described — it only catches that the extraction code runs. The claim 'generated signature matches the expected interface' only fails with a real model.","test_description":"Send a natural language description with specific parameter names, types, and return type to the real LLM generation endpoint. Parse the returned code and extract the function signature. Assert that parameter names, annotated types, and return type all match the original spec. Run at least 3 representative descriptions covering different type combinations to reduce false-pass from lucky sampling.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.65,"Workflow":0.15}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The generated implementation passes all provided test cases on the first or a subsequent attempt.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: 'First or a subsequent attempt' explicitly requires the generate→test→refine→test loop to execute at least once and potentially multiple times. Verifying that the system eventually produces passing code requires: (1) a real LLM generating real code, (2) real code execution against the test suite, and (3) the refinement cycle actually running when the first attempt fails. LLM-DEP: A stub LLM that always returns working code trivially passes; one that always fails never demonstrates success. The real failure mode — the LLM gets it right on attempt 2 or 3 — only surfaces when a non-deterministic model is allowed to iterate. REJECTION of Agentic: A single Agentic call cannot cover 'subsequent attempt'; the multi-step feedback loop is load-bearing. REAL-INFRA: Running generated code against test cases requires real subprocess execution — an in-process fake cannot replicate actual code execution failures.","test_description":"Choose a function whose correct implementation is non-trivial (e.g., dynamic programming or recursive algorithm). Run the full service pipeline with the real LLM and real test execution subprocess. Assert that after at most 3 attempts, all provided test cases pass and the final result status is 'success'. Record which attempt number succeeded to verify the refinement path was exercised.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.15,"Workflow":0.75}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When tests fail, the refinement step includes the failure messages in the next LLM prompt so the model can learn from its mistakes.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is at the boundary between the test-execution module and the prompt-construction module: failure messages from the test runner must be correctly threaded into the next prompt. This is not a single-function concern — it requires the pipeline wiring to propagate test output. MOCK-HIDE: We do NOT need a real LLM to verify prompt content. A stub LLM that captures the prompt it receives is sufficient — we can assert that the captured prompt contains the exact failure messages from the test run. Using a real LLM would not improve the test; what matters is the data flowing *into* the LLM, not the LLM's response. REAL-INFRA: The test runner that produces failure messages can be real (running deterministic always-failing test fixtures) without requiring real network or OS behavior beyond subprocess. REJECTION of Agentic: LLM output quality is irrelevant here; we are verifying prompt content, not model behavior.","test_description":"Wire together the test-execution module and the prompt-construction module with a stub LLM that records every prompt it receives. Force the first generated code to fail by using a test suite that the stub's initial output cannot pass (pre-seeded stub response). Capture the second prompt. Assert that it contains the specific assertion error messages and stdout from the failed test run, not just a generic 'tests failed' placeholder.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.07,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The service stops after 3 failed attempts and returns a structured error with all three attempts and their test results.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The retry counter, attempt accumulator, and structured error builder must interact correctly — this is a module-boundary concern, not a single-function concern. A unit test on the counter alone does not verify that attempts and results are correctly collected and returned in the final error structure. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbing the LLM to always return code that fails tests, and stubbing the test runner to always report specific failures, will faithfully exercise the stop condition. Real LLM output is irrelevant — the failure mode (counter not incrementing, attempts not collected, wrong structure) appears with deterministic stubs. REAL-INFRA: No real subprocess, OS, or network needed; in-process fake test runner and stub LLM are sufficient. REJECTION of Agentic: The behavior is about control flow and data structure, not LLM output quality.","test_description":"Configure stub LLM to always return syntactically valid but semantically incorrect code. Configure stub test runner to always return distinct, identifiable failure messages for each run. Invoke the service. Assert: (1) exactly 3 LLM calls were made, (2) the returned error contains an array of 3 attempt objects, (3) each attempt object contains the generated code and the corresponding test failure output from that specific round, and (4) the overall status is 'failure'.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full loop — generate, test, refine, test again — produces a working implementation for a function that a single LLM call typically gets wrong.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: The behavior explicitly names the full pipeline (generate → test → refine → test) as load-bearing. It is not enough that any single step works; the emergent outcome from the iterative interaction of all steps must be verified. LLM-DEP: 'A function that a single LLM call typically gets wrong' makes real LLM non-determinism a requirement — the test must demonstrate that the feedback loop produces a correct result that single-shot generation reliably fails to produce. A stub LLM trivially passes or fails regardless of refinement quality. REAL-INFRA: Running the generated code against a real test suite requires real subprocess execution to surface actual runtime errors the LLM needs to correct. REJECTION of Agentic: A single Agentic call cannot cover the multi-step refinement loop that is central to this behavior. The feedback loop is not incidental; it is the thing being tested.","test_description":"Select a function known to be difficult for single-shot LLM generation (e.g., a specific edge-case-heavy algorithm). First, run the service with max_attempts=1 and assert it fails. Then run the full service (max_attempts=3) and assert it succeeds. The contrast between the single-shot failure and multi-attempt success demonstrates that the refinement loop is causally responsible for the correct result. Capture all attempt logs to confirm the feedback cycle (failure messages) appeared in subsequent prompts.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.12,"Workflow":0.8}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9911,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9911},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"96de98a5-37a6-4f51-9ce0-9ef3eef720d8","uuid":"afe8a36a-b9f7-48a8-b5a2-7eeac4b10f0a"}
